title: No. 11 Warriors split at Winterset Tournament
text:
Buy Photo Norwalk high school Warriors (Photo: The Register) Buy Photo
CONNECT TWEET LINKEDIN COMMENT EMAIL MORE Norwalk won its first two matches on Saturday, but dropped the back two as they went 2-2 at the Winterset Tournament in the team’s final regular season tournament of the season.
Match 1: Norwalk 2, Atlantic 0 (21-14, 21-8)
The Warriors were too much for Atlantic (2-19), recording a robust .512 kill percentage while acing nine serves on their way to a straight sets win.
Ryley Harris had four of those aces, hitting .800 for four kills while assisting on 17 kills to help propel the Warriors to their 23rd win of the season.
Tori VanVelzen led with five kills and Gabby Ridgeway had a team-best 15 digs.
Match 2: Norwalk 2, Hampton-Dumont 0 (21-10, 21-6)
Norwalk was just as dominating in match two of the day, notching 10 aces while having a .538 kill efficiency and seven total blocks to cruise by Hampton-Dumont (7-21).
The Warriors only had to make 21 total digs, keeping Hampton-Dumont on the defensive for much of the match while Amber Johnson, VanVelzen and Ridgeway led the way with five kills apiece.
Kiley Westhoff had a team-best three blocks as Ashlie Van Gorder and Harris had three aces apiece.
Match 3: Winterset 2, Norwalk 1 (21-16, 11-21, 15-11)
Winterset (18-8) had a kill efficiency of only .096 but they managed to put up 83 kill attempts and 10 aces to squeak past Norwalk in three sets.
Ridgeway had six kills to lead the Warriors who had a better kill efficiency at .143.
Harris was the only player with an assist, recording 19 and Clare Anderson dug out 21 shots to lead the Warriors in the loss.
Match 4: Gilbert 2, Norwalk 0 (20-25, 21-25)
It may have been a straight sets loss but the match was much closer than that.
A 24-10 Gilbert team worked around five kills from VanVelzen, Ridgeway and Harris to earn the edge in both sets.
Norwalk didn’t have a poor attack, posting a .179 kill percentage but the Warriors’ numbers were slightly down in aces (6) and total blocks (4).
Harris had 18 assists and Anderson 15 digs, both team-bests in the respective categories.
Coming Up:
Norwalk sits at 24-10 on the season and in good position for postseason play at No. 11 in Class 4A. The Warriors finished up their regular season play on Tuesday, Oct. 20 against Newton in Norwalk.
